In this speech, President Biden addresses a gathering at a private residence in New York. He thanks the attendees and mentions that the third reason he ran for president was to unite the country, which he admits has been the hardest thing to do. He acknowledges the support and help he received from Democratic representatives and highlights the achievements of his administration, such as creating jobs and revitalizing the manufacturing sector. He also criticizes the current Republican Party, accusing them of wanting to get rid of Social Security and Medicare in order to cut the deficit. He emphasizes the importance of addressing climate change and rebuilding America's relationships with its allies. He talks about the need for better education and affordable healthcare, and the importance of fair taxation. He concludes by expressing his optimism about America's future and his determination to make the country economically strong.